{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774289881,"nonce":"b2Vjhhvy0VirKw8JMLo0NNEWuj0=","title":"Adaptation vs. robustness distinguishability in trained networks","message":"## Summary\n\nBackprop-trained RNNs receiving SISU may learn to ADAPT (predict perturbation statistics, adjust feedforward) rather than genuinely ROBUSTEN (increase feedback gains, general stiffness). This tracks the problem and proposed supplementary analyses.\n\n## The Core Problem\n\nAdaptation = trial-by-trial internal model update, direction-specific feedforward cancellation.\nRobustness = feedback gain/impedance changes, non-specific, rapid, no perturbation-specific knowledge needed.\n\nEven PAI-ASF, which prevents feedforward cancellation of specific realizations, still allows \"adaptive gain scheduling\" — scaling control effort with beta without changing qualitative strategy. This is mechanistically different from making the closed-loop system insensitive to disturbances.\n\nGemini framing: this is a System Identification vs. Control trade-off. The network may allocate capacity to identifying the perturbation regime rather than developing a genuinely robust control law.\n\n## Existing Evidence\n\nPartial evidence for robustness: Part 2 networks benefit from SISU. If purely adaptive, they'd estimate field parameters from early sensory feedback regardless of SISU. The fact that SISU matters suggests it's used beyond what online estimation provides.\n\n## Proposed Supplementary Analyses\n\n### 1. Direction-Reversal Probe (Mid-Trial Field Flip)\nEvaluate with field in one direction, reverse midway. If adaptive: large asymmetric error spike (internal estimate suddenly wrong). If robust: symmetric recovery. Challenge: calibrate magnitudes so deviations are comparable.\n\n### 2. Regression of Late Forces Against Early Perturbation Parameters\nRegress late-trial control forces against actual sampled parameter values. If robust: forces correlate with SISU but NOT actual parameter. If adaptive: forces track actual parameter estimate.\n\n### 3. SISU-High Catch Trials\nSISU = 1 but no actual perturbation. If adaptive: initial force bias (pushing against absent perturbation). If robust: higher feedback gains but no directional force bias.\n\n### 4. Forward Model Analysis\nCompare network's implicit forward model under adaptation (CW curl) vs. robustening (mixed-direction curl). Adaptive network should show direction-specific prediction improvements.\n\n## Severity by Training Method\n- DAI: most severe (direct amplitude enables adaptation)\n- BCS: moderate\n- PAI-ASF: least severe (prevents feedforward cancellation of realizations)\n- Only adversarial training would structurally prevent adaptation\n\n## Status\nProposed analyses not yet implemented. Field-reversal and regression approaches described in manuscript/results.md as planned work.\n\nCo-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.6 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e, Gemini 3.1 Pro Preview \u003cnoreply@google.com\u003e","files":null}]}